window.DATA={"meta":{"title":"The World Through Time","subtitle":"A visual history of the world from the first humans to 1945 — the line of the prophets on one rail, the wider world on the other","endnote":"Ends 1945: the UN, two superpowers, and the modern borders — the map fades toward today."},"zones":[{"id":"z1","label":"Zone 1 · The Age of the Prophets","sub":"Undated deep time — true order, real places, no invented years"},{"id":"z2","label":"Zone 2 · The Dated Ancient World","sub":"~2000 BC – 570 CE — eras anchored to datable civilizations"},{"id":"z3","label":"Zone 3 · Recorded History","sub":"570 – 1945 CE — year-by-year precision; the AH rail begins at the migration to Madinah (the Hijrah)"}],"milestones":[{"id":"1","num":"1","side":"i","sort":-100000,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"Undated — the beginning","ah":null,"title":"Adam and Eve (Adam and Hawwa) — the beginning of humanity","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Mecca — first House of worship","Bakkah → Makkah, Saudi Arabia",21.42,39.83],["Adam's Peak (reported tradition)","Sarandib → Sri Lanka",6.81,80.5],["Reunion at Arafat (reported)","Arafat, near Mecca",21.35,39.98]],"story":"God (Allah) created Adam (peace be upon him), taught him the names of all things, and commanded the angels to bow; Satan (Iblis) refused out of pride. After the Garden and the first repentance, Adam and Eve (Hawwa) began the human story on Earth with a promise: guidance would come, and whoever follows it will not fear nor grieve. Their sons Abel and Cain (Habil and Qabil) enact the first crime — the first murder. The Quran ties the first House of worship to Bakkah: Mecca.","meanwhile":"By definition, nothing — this is the start of the human story. The map shows a borderless Earth.","pop":"The first humans","src":"Q 2:30–39; 7:11–25; 20:115–123; 5:27–31; 3:96 · Ibn Kathir (Stories of the Prophets; al-Bidayah) · al-Tabari v.1"},{"id":"2","num":"2","side":"i","sort":-99000,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"Undated — before Nuh","ah":null,"title":"Enoch (Idris) — the first to write","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Babylon (reported)","Babil → Hillah, Iraq",32.54,44.42],["Memphis, Egypt (reported)","Men-nefer → Mit Rahina",29.85,31.25]],"story":"“A man of truth and a prophet, and We raised him to a high station” (Q 19:56–57). Tradition credits Enoch (peace be upon him) as the first to write with the pen, to sew garments, and to study the stars — humanity's first scholar-prophet, remembered at the very dawn of writing.","meanwhile":"Farming villages dot the Fertile Crescent, the Nile, the Indus and the Yellow River — the seedbeds of the first civilizations.","pop":"~5–10M worldwide (est.)","src":"Q 19:56–57; 21:85 · Stories of the Prophets"},{"id":"3","num":"3","side":"i","sort":-98000,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"Undated — 950 years of calling","ah":null,"title":"Noah (Nuh) — the Flood","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["His people — Mesopotamia","Lower Iraq",31.0,45.5],["The Ark rested on Mount Judi","Cudi Dağı, SE Turkey",37.37,42.34]],"story":"Idolatry entered the world — Wadd, Suwa, Yaghuth, Ya'uq, Nasr began as venerated righteous men. Noah (peace be upon him) called for 950 years; few believed. Commanded to build the Ark, he watched the Flood take the deniers, his own son among them. Humanity restarted from the believers. The Quran names Mount Judi — not Ararat — as the resting place.","meanwhile":"Mesopotamian tablets — the Sumerian flood story, later Gilgamesh — preserve a cross-civilizational memory of a great deluge.","pop":null,"src":"Q 71; 11:25–49; 29:14; 37:75–82 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Tabari v.1"},{"id":"4","num":"4","side":"i","sort":-97000,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"Undated — after Nuh","ah":null,"title":"Hud — the people of 'Aad","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Al-Ahqaf, the curved dunes","Hadhramaut / Empty Quarter, Yemen–Oman",17.5,51.0],["Iram of the Pillars (possible: Ubar)","Shisr, Oman",18.25,53.65]],"story":"'Aad were mighty builders — “the like of whom was never created in the lands” — raising monuments on every height. They answered Hud (peace be upon him) with arrogance in their strength, and a screaming wind unmade them over seven nights and eight days.","meanwhile":"Southern Arabia later becomes the frankincense corridor — the caravan road north to the Levant.","pop":null,"src":"Q 7:65–72; 46:21–26; 69:6–8; 89:6–8 · Stories of the Prophets"},{"id":"5","num":"5","side":"i","sort":-96000,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"Undated — after 'Aad","ah":null,"title":"Salih — the Thamud and the she-camel","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Al-Hijr — rock-cut homes","Mada'in Salih / Hegra, AlUla, Saudi Arabia",26.79,37.95]],"story":"Thamud carved homes from mountains with skill. They demanded a sign: a she-camel emerged from rock with an appointed share of water. They hamstrung her in defiance; after three days the blast seized them. The Prophet (PBUH) later passed this valley weeping, telling his companions to hurry through.","meanwhile":"Northwest Arabia sits on the artery that becomes the incense road; today's visible tombs at Hegra are the later Nabataean layer over the Thamudic homeland.","pop":null,"src":"Q 7:73–79; 11:61–68; 91:11–15 · Stories of the Prophets · Sealed Nectar (Tabuk)"},{"id":"6","num":"6","side":"i","sort":-2000,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~2000–1800 BC","ah":null,"title":"Abraham (Ibrahim) — the friend of God","map":"bc2000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Ur — birthplace (tradition)","Tell el-Muqayyar, Iraq",30.96,46.1],["Babylon — the fire of Nimrod","Hillah, Iraq",32.54,44.42],["Harran — migration stop","Harran, Turkey",36.87,39.03],["Hebron — his home; named for him","Al-Khalil, Palestine",31.53,35.1],["Mecca — raising the Kaaba (the cube-shaped House of worship at Mecca)","Makkah",21.42,39.83],["Sodom — the people of Lut (peace be upon him)","Dead Sea region",31.5,35.5]],"story":"Raised among idol-carvers, Abraham (peace be upon him) reasoned from star, moon and sun to the One Creator, smashed his people's idols, walked out of Nimrod's fire unharmed, and migrated for God (Allah)'s sake — Ur, Harran, Palestine, Egypt, Mecca. Tested with the sacrifice of Ismail, ransomed by God (Allah). With Ismail he raised the Kaaba (the cube-shaped House of worship at Mecca)'s foundations and proclaimed the pilgrimage. In the same era Lut (peace be upon him) was sent to Sodom by the Dead Sea. Dated history on this timeline begins here.","meanwhile":"Middle Kingdom Egypt; Babylon rising toward Hammurabi; the Indus cities at their height; Stonehenge already standing; the first American cities (Caral) old news in Peru.","pop":"World ~27M · Egypt ~1–1.5M","src":"Q 6:74–83; 21:51–70; 2:124–132, 258; 37:99–113; 14:35–41 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Tabari v.2 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"7","num":"7","side":"i","sort":-1900,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~1900–1700 BC","ah":null,"title":"Ishmael and Isaac (Ismail and Ishaq) — two family lines","map":"bc2000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Mecca — Hajar, Zamzam, the Kaaba (the cube-shaped House of worship at Mecca)","Makkah",21.42,39.83],["Canaan — Ishaq's land","Hebron/Beersheba region",31.5,35.0]],"story":"The infant Ismail and his mother Hajar, left in the barren valley by God (Allah)'s command; her running between Safa and Marwah; Zamzam springing at the child's feet; the Jurhum settling by the water — the founding of Mecca itself, re-enacted by every pilgrim since. Ishmael (peace be upon him) fathered the northern Arabs — the line of Muhammad (PBUH). Isaac (peace be upon him), promised son of Ibrahim's old age, carried prophethood among the Children of Israel (Bani Israil).","meanwhile":"Hammurabi's law code (~1750 BC) in Babylon; Egypt slides toward the Hyksos era; the Indus cities quietly decline.","pop":"World ~27–35M","src":"Q 2:125–129; 37:100–113; 19:54–55 · Sahih al-Bukhari (story of Zamzam) · Stories of the Prophets"},{"id":"8","num":"8","side":"i","sort":-1750,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~1800–1600 BC","ah":null,"title":"Jacob and Joseph (Yaqub and Yusuf) — into Egypt","map":"bc1500","panel":"p1","pins":[["Canaan → Egypt","Palestine to the Nile Delta",31.0,34.8],["Yusuf's Egypt","Memphis / eastern Delta",29.85,31.25]],"story":"“The best of stories” (Q 12): the dream, the brothers' betrayal, the well, slavery, the trial, prison, the king's dream of seven fat and seven lean years — and Joseph (peace be upon him) rising to run Egypt's storehouses through famine, drawing Yaqub's family into Egypt. This is how the Children of Israel (Bani Israil) came to the Nile — the stage-setting for Moses (peace be upon him).","meanwhile":"Egypt's Hyksos period — foreign kings in the Delta, a context many find consistent with Yusuf's story; Minoan Crete trades across the sea; Shang China's first writing approaches.","pop":"World ~30–40M · Egypt ~2M","src":"Q 12 (entire surah) · Stories of the Prophets · al-Tabari v.2"},{"id":"9","num":"9","side":"i","sort":-1500,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"Between Yusuf & Musa","ah":null,"title":"Job (Ayyub), Dhul-Kifl, and Jethro (Shu'ayb)","map":"bc1500","panel":"p2","pins":[["Ayyub — land of Hauran (reports)","S. Syria / N. Jordan",32.5,36.5],["Dhul-Kifl — shrine tradition","Al-Kifl, Iraq",32.23,44.37],["Shu'ayb — Madyan","al-Bad', NW Saudi Arabia",28.5,35.0]],"story":"Job (peace be upon him): wealth, children and health stripped away, trust unbroken — “We found him patient; an excellent servant.” Dhul-Kifl: named among the steadfast. Jethro (Shu'ayb) (peace be upon him) was sent to Madyan, traders who cheated the scales and cut the road; his message fused pure worship with commercial honesty — give full measure and full weight — the merchant ethics that return in Muhammad's (PBUH) Mecca.","meanwhile":"Late Bronze Age trade at its peak — Egyptian, Hittite, Aegean and Babylonian worlds linked by sea and caravan; Madyan sits on the copper and incense routes, which is exactly why weights and measures were the moral battlefield.","pop":"World ~40M","src":"Q 38:41–44; 21:83–85; 7:85–93; 11:84–95 · Stories of the Prophets"},{"id":"10","num":"10","side":"i","sort":-1250,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~13th century BC","ah":null,"title":"Moses and Aaron (Musa and Harun) — confronting Pharaoh","map":"bc1500","panel":"p2","pins":[["Born under the edict","Pi-Ramesses / E. Delta, Egypt",30.8,31.8],["Ten years in Madyan","al-Bad', NW Arabia",28.5,35.0],["The burning bush; the Torah","Mount Tur / Jabal Musa, Sinai",28.54,33.98],["The sea crossing","Red Sea / Gulf of Suez",29.5,32.6]],"story":"The baby set on the Nile and raised in Pharaoh's own house; the call at the burning bush — “Indeed, I am God (Allah)”; nine signs; sorcerers who believed; the Exodus and the parted sea; Pharaoh drowned — “today We preserve your body as a sign”; the golden calf; the Torah at Sinai; Qarun swallowed; the journey with the mysterious teacher al-Khidr. Moses (peace be upon him) is the most-mentioned prophet in the Quran. The Quran never names the Pharaoh — his identity is debated.","meanwhile":"New Kingdom Egypt at imperial peak (era of Ramesses II by convention); the Hittites sign history's first surviving peace treaty after Kadesh; Mycenaean Greece; Shang oracle bones; the Olmec rising in Mexico — and within decades, the entire Bronze Age system will crash.","pop":"World ~40–50M · Egypt ~2–3M","src":"Q 20:9–98; 28:3–46; 26:10–68; 10:75–92; 18:60–82 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Tabari v.3"},{"id":"11","num":"11","side":"i","sort":-1000,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~1000–930 BC","ah":null,"title":"Joshua, David and Solomon (Yusha, Dawud, Sulayman) — the kingdom in the Holy Land","map":"bc1000","panel":"p3","pins":[["Jerusalem — Dawud's city, Sulayman's Temple","Al-Quds / Jerusalem",31.78,35.23],["Saba — kingdom of Bilqis","Marib, Yemen",15.42,45.34]],"story":"After Moses (peace be upon him), Joshua (peace be upon him) led the Children of Israel (Bani Israil) into the Holy Land. Generations later the young Dawud slew Goliath (Jalut) and became prophet-king — iron softened for him, mountains echoing his praise, the Zabur revealed. Solomon (peace be upon him) ruled as no one before or since: wind subjected, unseen beings (jinn) building, the speech of birds understood; the hoopoe's report of Saba, Bilqis's throne brought in a blink, her submission to God (Allah); the Temple raised at Bayt al-Maqdis. After him, the kingdom split.","meanwhile":"Egypt weak; Assyria gathering; Zhou China proclaims the Mandate of Heaven; Tyre's Phoenician traders spread the alphabet; the Saba–Jerusalem axis of the Bilqis story is the incense road itself.","pop":"World ~50M","src":"Q 2:246–251; 21:78–82; 27:15–44; 34:10–16; 38:17–40 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Tabari v.3"},{"id":"12","num":"12","side":"i","sort":-800,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~9th–8th century BC","ah":null,"title":"Elijah, Elisha and Jonah (Ilyas, Al-Yasa, Yunus) — and the whale","map":"bc700","panel":"p3","pins":[["Ilyas — against Baal-worship","Baalbek region / N. Israel",34.0,36.2],["Yunus — sent to Nineveh","Mosul, Iraq",36.36,43.15]],"story":"Elijah (peace be upon him) called the northern kingdom away from Baal; Elisha (peace be upon him) continued after him. Jonah (peace be upon him) left his city before God (Allah)'s leave; the storm, the lots, the great fish — and the cry in triple darkness: “There is no deity except You; exalted are You; I was of the wrongdoers.” His city — uniquely in the Quran — believed en masse and was spared: Nineveh, the biggest city of its age.","meanwhile":"Assyria is the superpower whose capital region is Nineveh itself; first Olympics (776 BC); Rome's legendary founding (753 BC); Homer's epics take shape.","pop":"World ~60–80M · Nineveh 100,000+ — matching Q 37:147","src":"Q 37:123–148; 21:87–88; 10:98; 68:48–50 · Stories of the Prophets"},{"id":"12b","num":"12b","side":"i","sort":-700,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"Undated — Quranic figures","ah":null,"title":"Dhul-Qarnayn and Luqman — a just king and a wise man","map":"bc500","panel":"p3","pins":[["The barrier against Yajuj & Majuj — location debated","Caucasus / Central Asian pass traditions",42.5,44.5]],"story":"Dhul-Qarnayn — a righteous king given power over the earth — traveled to the world's extremes, judged with justice, built the barrier and refused payment: “This is a mercy from my Lord.” The Quran deliberately does not name him: classical scholars often said Alexander; many later scholars argue Cyrus; the site presents both (see W8 and W11). Luqman the Wise counseled his son — gratitude, prayer, humility, “do not walk the earth in arrogance” — a sage, most scholars hold, rather than a prophet.","meanwhile":"Cross-reference: World Track W8 (Cyrus) and W11 (Alexander) — the two candidacies, side by side.","pop":null,"src":"Q 18:83–98; 31:12–19 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Bidayah v.2"},{"id":"13","num":"13","side":"i","sort":1,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~1–33 CE","ah":null,"title":"Zechariah, John, Mary and Jesus (Zakariya, Yahya, Maryam, Isa)","map":"bc1","panel":"p4","pins":[["Zakariya's sanctuary; Mary (Maryam)'s chamber","Jerusalem / Al-Quds",31.78,35.23],["The palm and the stream","Bethlehem / Bayt Lahm",31.7,35.2],["Isa's ministry","Nazareth & Galilee",32.7,35.3]],"story":"Zechariah (peace be upon him), granted Yahya in old age — “We gave him judgment while yet a boy.” Mary (Maryam), chosen above the women of the worlds, conceives Jesus (peace be upon him) by God (Allah)'s word — “Be, and it is.” The infant speaks from the cradle: “I am the servant of God (Allah).” He heals the blind and the leper and revives the dead by God (Allah)'s permission, brings the Gospel (Injil) — and the Islamic account is explicit: they did not kill him nor crucify him, but it was made to appear so; God (Allah) raised him to Himself. Muslims await his return. John (peace be upon him) was martyred by the ruler of his day. Here Islamic and Christian narratives visibly diverge; both are stated, the Islamic account leads.","meanwhile":"Rome under Tiberius holds Judea through prefects — Jesus (peace be upon him) preaches inside an occupation; Parthia faces Rome; Han China censuses 57 million; the Silk Road links silk to denarius; Aksum rises in Ethiopia; Teotihuacan grows toward 100,000.","pop":"World ~170M (est. up to ~300M) · Rome ~1M","src":"Q 3:33–59; 19:2–36; 4:157–159; 5:110–118 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Bidayah v.2"},{"id":"14b","num":"14b","side":"i","sort":250,"dated":false,"yearLabel":"~3rd–5th century CE (commentators)","ah":null,"title":"The Sleepers in the Cave (Ashab al-Kahf)","map":"400","panel":"p4","pins":[["Ephesus tradition","Near Selçuk, Turkey",37.94,27.34],["Amman tradition","Al-Rajib, Jordan",31.9,35.95]],"story":"Young believers fled a city that persecuted monotheism; God (Allah) cast sleep over them “three hundred years, and add nine.” They woke thinking a day had passed — and their obsolete coins betrayed the centuries. The Quran makes them the emblem of the interval itself: pure faith preserved through an age of persecution. They fled a pagan empire and woke in a Christian one — the exact arc of W15.","meanwhile":"Most commentators place the flight under Roman persecution (~250 CE) and the awakening in the Theodosian 5th century.","pop":null,"src":"Q 18:9–26 · Stories of the Prophets · al-Bidayah v.2"},{"id":"14","num":"14","side":"i","sort":300,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~33–570 CE","ah":null,"title":"The Long Gap (Fatrah) — five centuries with no new prophet","map":"400","panel":"p4","pins":[["Nicaea — the creed fixed under Constantine","İznik, Turkey",40.43,29.72],["Najran — the People of the Ukhdud","Najran, Saudi Arabia",17.49,44.13],["Abraha's elephant army destroyed","Approach to Mecca",21.3,39.9]],"story":"No new messenger for five centuries. Isa's (peace be upon him) message spreads — and transforms under Roman patronage; Nicaea (325) fixes the trinitarian creed the Quran addresses. True monotheists persist in pockets — Salman al-Farsi's journey from Persia through monasteries to Madinah is this era's human face. In Yemen, the believers of Najran are burned in the trench (~523) — remembered in Surah al-Buruj. In 570 Abraha marches an elephant army against the Kaaba (the cube-shaped House of worship at Mecca) and is destroyed by flights of birds — the very year the Prophet (PBUH) is born.","meanwhile":"Rome falls in the West (476); Justinian's plague hollows the empires; the Gupta age gives the world zero; China reunifies under the Sui; Aksum and Persia fight over Yemen.","pop":"World ~190–200M by 600 CE","src":"Q 5:19; 4:171; 85:4–8; 105 · Sealed Nectar (opening) · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"15","num":"15","side":"i","sort":570,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"570 CE","ah":null,"title":"The Year of the Elephant — birth of Muhammad (PBUH)","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Born in Mecca","Makkah",21.42,39.83]],"story":"Born into Banu Hashim — noble, not wealthy; orphaned of father before birth, of mother at six. Raised by Abdul-Muttalib, then Abu Talib; nursed among Banu Sa'd in the desert. Shepherd, then trader — the city itself names him al-Amin, the Trustworthy. At 25 he marries Khadijah; at 35 his arbitration of the Black Stone dispute averts a tribal war.","meanwhile":"Justin II in Byzantium; Khosrow Anushirvan's Persia at its cultural peak; plague recurs across the Mediterranean; in 589 the Sui unify China.","pop":"World ~190M","src":"Q 105 · Sealed Nectar · al-Bidayah v.3 · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"16","num":"16","side":"i","sort":610,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"610 CE · Ramadan","ah":null,"title":"The cave of Hira — “Read!”","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Cave of Hira, Jabal al-Nur","Outside Mecca",21.46,39.86]],"story":"At forty, in his habitual retreat, the angel Gabriel (Jibril) (peace be upon him) comes: “Read in the name of your Lord who created.” Khadijah believes first; Waraqah recognizes the same Namus that came to Musa and warns his people will expel him. Three quiet years: Abu Bakr, Ali, Zayd, Bilal — the first circle.","meanwhile":"In this same year Heraclius seizes the Byzantine throne mid-catastrophe as Persia overruns Syria — the empires' death-grapple and the revelation begin together.","pop":null,"src":"Q 96:1–5; 74:1–7 · Sahih al-Bukhari (Book of Revelation) · Sealed Nectar"},{"id":"17","num":"17","side":"i","sort":613,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"613–615 CE","ah":null,"title":"Public preaching, persecution, Abyssinia","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Proclamation on Safa","Mecca",21.42,39.83],["Refuge with the Negus","Aksum, Ethiopia",14.13,38.72]],"story":"Commanded to proclaim openly, he stands on Safa; Abu Lahab's curse is answered by Surah 111. Persecution: Bilal under the boulder — “Ahad! Ahad!”; Sumayyah, the first martyr. Eighty-plus Muslims cross the Red Sea to Christian Aksum; Ja'far recites Surah Mary (Maryam) and the Negus weeps and refuses to surrender them — the first international protection of Muslims, granted by a Christian king.","meanwhile":"Persia takes Jerusalem itself (614), carrying off the True Cross; Meccan idolaters gloat — and Surah ar-Rum answers with a prophecy: Rome will win “within a few years.”","pop":null,"src":"Q 111; 30:1–5; 19 · Sealed Nectar (First Migration)"},{"id":"18","num":"18","side":"i","sort":617,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"617–620 CE","ah":null,"title":"The boycott, the Year of Sorrow, Ta'if","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Shi'b Abi Talib — the boycott ravine","Mecca",21.42,39.84],["Stoned at Ta'if","Ta'if, Saudi Arabia",21.27,40.42]],"story":"Quraysh seal Banu Hashim in a ravine — starvation years. Then both protectors die in one year: Khadijah and Abu Talib. At Ta'if the mob stones him until his sandals fill with blood; to the angel of the mountains he answers only: “I hope God (Allah) will bring from their descendants those who worship God (Allah) alone.”","meanwhile":"Persia completes the conquest of Egypt (619); Byzantium contemplates abandoning Constantinople — the old order collapses exactly as the Prophet's (PBUH) position hits its lowest.","pop":null,"src":"Sahih al-Bukhari & Muslim · Sealed Nectar (Year of Grief; To Ta'if)"},{"id":"19","num":"19","side":"i","sort":621,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~620–621 CE","ah":null,"title":"Isra & Mi'raj — the Night Journey","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["From al-Masjid al-Haram","Mecca",21.42,39.83],["To al-Masjid al-Aqsa","Jerusalem / Al-Quds",31.776,35.235]],"story":"“Exalted is He who took His Servant by night from al-Masjid al-Haram to al-Masjid al-Aqsa.” He leads the prophets in prayer at Jerusalem and ascends through the heavens; the five daily prayers are given. Abu Bakr earns the title as-Siddiq. Mecca and Jerusalem are welded together in Islamic geography.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Q 17:1; 53:1–18 · Sealed Nectar (Night Journey)"},{"id":"20","num":"20","side":"i","sort":622,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"622 CE","ah":"1 AH","title":"THE HIJRAH — Year One","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Three days in the cave","Cave of Thawr",21.38,39.85],["Yathrib becomes Madinah","Madinah",24.47,39.61],["First mosque","Quba, Madinah",24.44,39.62]],"story":"Pledges of Aqabah; the assassination plot; Ali in the Prophet's (PBUH) bed; “Do not grieve — God (Allah) is with us” in the cave. Arrival at Yathrib: the first mosque, the brotherhood pairing each Emigrant with a Helper — history's most famous refugee integration — and the Constitution of Madinah binding Muslims and Jewish tribes into one defensive community. The Islamic calendar counts from this year: the AH rail begins here.","meanwhile":"The very year of the migration to Madinah (the Hijrah), Heraclius launches his counter-offensive against Persia; Tang China is four years old; Maya kings raise day-dated stelae across the ocean.","pop":"World ~200M","src":"Q 9:40; 8:30 · Sealed Nectar (The Hijrah) · al-Tabari v.6–7"},{"id":"21","num":"21","side":"i","sort":624,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"624 CE","ah":"2 AH · 17 Ramadan","title":"Badr — the Criterion","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["The wells of Badr","Badr, Saudi Arabia",23.78,38.79]],"story":"313 ill-equipped believers face a thousand. “God (Allah) gave you victory at Badr while you were few.” Abu Jahl falls; Arabia's balance shifts. Literate prisoners ransom themselves by teaching Muslims to read. Weeks earlier the direction of prayer (qiblah) had turned from Jerusalem to the Kaaba (the cube-shaped House of worship at Mecca).","meanwhile":"Heraclius is deep in Persian Armenia; the superpowers never notice the skirmish at a desert well that will outlive them both.","pop":null,"src":"Q 8 (al-Anfal); 3:123–127 · Sealed Nectar · al-Tabari v.7"},{"id":"22","num":"22","side":"i","sort":625,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"625 CE","ah":"3 AH · Shawwal","title":"Uhud — the wound and the lesson","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Mount Uhud","North of Madinah",24.5,39.61]],"story":"Quraysh return three-thousand strong. Early success unravels when the archers leave their hill; Khalid — then a pagan — wheels the cavalry; the Prophet (PBUH) is wounded; Hamzah is martyred and mutilated. The Quran turns defeat into curriculum in fifty-nine verses.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Q 3:121–179 · Sealed Nectar · al-Bidayah v.4"},{"id":"23","num":"23","side":"i","sort":627,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"627 CE","ah":"5 AH","title":"Al-Khandaq — the Trench","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["The trench on Madinah's north","Madinah",24.49,39.59]],"story":"Ten thousand confederates besiege Madinah. On Salman al-Farsi's Persian advice the Muslims dig a trench — foreign military technology adopted overnight. Storm winds and unseen forces break the siege. “This year we raid them, and they will not raid us” — the tide has turned.","meanwhile":"In the same months Heraclius crushes Persia at Nineveh — on the ground of Yunus's city — fulfilling Surah ar-Rum within the prophesied “few years”; Khosrow II falls in 628. Both sieges of the age break within weeks of each other.","pop":null,"src":"Q 33:9–27 · Sealed Nectar · al-Tabari v.8"},{"id":"24","num":"24","side":"i","sort":628,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"628 CE","ah":"6 AH","title":"Hudaybiyyah — the treaty that was a victory","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["The pledge under the tree","Hudaybiyyah, edge of Mecca's sanctuary",21.44,39.61]],"story":"1,400 unarmed pilgrims blocked from the lesser pilgrimage (Umrah); the Pledge under the Tree; a ten-year truce on terms that looked humiliating — and the Quran names it “a clear victory.” Peace opens the roads: more enter Islam in two years than in the previous nineteen. From here, letters go to the rulers of the earth: Heraclius, Khosrow, the Negus, Muqawqis — four routes radiating from Madinah.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Q 48 (al-Fath) · Sealed Nectar (Letters to the Kings)"},{"id":"25","num":"25","side":"i","sort":630,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"630 CE","ah":"8 AH · Ramadan","title":"The Conquest of Mecca","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Entering bowed in humility","Mecca",21.42,39.83],["Hunayn & Ta'if follow","Hunayn valley",21.6,40.0]],"story":"The truce broken by Quraysh's allies; ten thousand enter Mecca almost bloodlessly. The 360 idols fall to “Truth has come and falsehood has vanished”; the general amnesty — “Go, for you are free”; Bilal, once tortured on these streets, calls the call to prayer (adhan) from the Kaaba (the cube-shaped House of worship at Mecca)'s roof. Hunayn, Ta'if, then Tabuk probe the Byzantine marches; the Year of Delegations brings Arabia's tribes in.","meanwhile":"In 630 Heraclius ceremonially returns the True Cross to Jerusalem — Byzantium's greatest moment, eight years before that city surrenders to Umar.","pop":null,"src":"Q 17:81; 110; 9:25–26 · Sealed Nectar · al-Tabari v.8–9"},{"id":"26","num":"26","side":"i","sort":632,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"632 CE","ah":"10–11 AH","title":"The Farewell Pilgrimage — and the passing (PBUH)","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["The Farewell Sermon","Arafat",21.35,39.98],["He passes in Madinah","Madinah",24.47,39.61]],"story":"Before a hundred thousand at Arafat: sanctity of life and property, usury and blood-feuds abolished, the rights of women, “no Arab is superior to a non-Arab except by piety” — and the verse descends: “This day I have perfected for you your religion.” Months later he passes in Aisha's chamber. Abu Bakr steadies the community (ummah): “Whoever worshipped Muhammad — Muhammad has died. Whoever worships God (Allah) — God (Allah) is Ever-Living.” At his passing, essentially all Arabia is one order — a polity that did not exist 23 years earlier.","meanwhile":null,"pop":"World ~200M · the community: ~100,000+ Muslims","src":"Q 5:3; 3:144 · Sahih al-Bukhari · Sealed Nectar (final chapters)"},{"id":"27","num":"27","side":"i","sort":633,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"632–634 CE","ah":"11–13 AH","title":"Abu Bakr — holding the centre","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Capital: Madinah","Madinah",24.47,39.61],["Yamamah — the costly victory","Central Arabia",24.1,47.3]],"story":"Chosen at Saqifah; mass apostasy and false prophets answered in the wars against the tribal rebellion (the Riddah wars) — Arabia re-unified within a year. After Yamamah's toll of Quran memorizers, Zayd ibn Thabit compiles the Quran into one written single bound copy (mushaf) — arguably history's most consequential act of textual preservation. Khalid probes Iraq; the first columns march on Byzantine Syria.","meanwhile":"Byzantium and Persia, bled white by 26 years of war, cannot hold their frontiers.","pop":null,"src":"al-Bidayah v.5 · al-Tabari v.10–11 · Sahih al-Bukhari"},{"id":"28","num":"28","side":"i","sort":638,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"634–644 CE","ah":"13–23 AH","title":"Umar — the map is redrawn in ten years","map":"700","panel":"p5","pins":[["Yarmouk 636 — Syria falls","Yarmouk river",32.75,35.95],["al-Qadisiyyah 636/7 — Persia's gate","Near Kufa, Iraq",31.6,44.5],["Jerusalem 638 — the Covenant of Umar","Al-Quds",31.78,35.23],["Egypt 639–642 — Fustat founded","Cairo",30.04,31.24],["Nihawand 642 — Victory of Victories","Nahavand, Iran",34.19,48.38]],"story":"Under al-Faruq the thousand-year two-empire order collapses: Yarmouk, Qadisiyyah, Ctesiphon, Jerusalem — where Umar arrives sharing his camel with his servant, refuses to pray inside the church so it will never be seized, and signs the Covenant guaranteeing Christian life, property and worship — then Egypt and Nihawand. He builds the machinery of a state: the Islamic calendar (Hijri), the stipend register, garrison cities (Basra, Kufa, Fustat), salaried judges, night patrols, famine management. Assassinated at prayer, 644.","meanwhile":"Heraclius dies watching his reconquest evaporate; Yazdegerd III flees east; the monk Xuanzang is walking across Harsha's India during these exact years — his travelogue is the best snapshot of the world Umar's couriers never saw.","pop":"Conquered lands ~15–20M people, governed from a mud-brick town","src":"al-Bidayah v.5 · al-Tabari v.12–14 · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"29","num":"29","side":"i","sort":650,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"644–656 CE","ah":"23–35 AH","title":"Uthman — one book, the first fleet, the first civil war","map":"700","panel":"p5","pins":[["The standard single bound copy (mushaf) sent to the provinces","Madinah",24.47,39.61],["Cyprus 649 — the first naval expedition","Cyprus",35.1,33.4]],"story":"Conquests reach Cyprus (the first fleet), North Africa, Armenia, Khurasan. As Islam spreads among non-Arabs, recitation variants alarm commanders; Uthman commissions the standard single bound copy (mushaf) — the same consonantal text every Muslim reads today — and sends master copies to the provinces. Agitators inflame grievances; rebels besiege his Madinah home and martyr him as he reads the Book he standardized.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Sahih al-Bukhari · al-Bidayah v.5 · al-Tabari v.15"},{"id":"30","num":"30","side":"i","sort":658,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"656–661 CE","ah":"35–40 AH","title":"Ali — the community divides","map":"700","panel":"p5","pins":[["Capital moves to Kufa","Kufa, Iraq",32.03,44.4],["Siffin 657","Upper Euphrates, Syria",35.95,39.02]],"story":"The Prophet's (PBUH) cousin inherits a community (ummah) demanding justice for Uthman while rebels stand in its ranks: the Camel, Siffin, the arbitration, an extremist splinter group (the Khawarij) schism — Islam's first extremists — and Nahrawan. Assassinated by a Kharijite (extremist splinter) at Fajr in Kufa's mosque, Ramadan 661. Al-Hasan abdicates to Muawiya months later, reuniting the community — the Year of Unity, fulfilling the Prophet's (PBUH) words. Here Sunni and Shia memory divides; this site narrates from classical Sunni sources and flags the divergence with respect.","meanwhile":"The political center of Islam leaves Arabia — never to return.","pop":null,"src":"al-Bidayah v.5 · al-Tabari v.16–17 · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"31","num":"31","side":"i","sort":670,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"661–683 CE","ah":"41–64 AH","title":"Muawiya's new order — and the killing at Karbala","map":"700","panel":"p6","pins":[["Capital: Damascus","Damascus, Syria",33.51,36.29],["Karbala — 10 Muharram 61 AH","Karbala, Iraq",32.62,44.03]],"story":"Muawiya governs with legendary forbearance — and turns the caliphate hereditary: the pivot from elective rule to dynastic kingship that Islamic sources themselves mark. First sieges of Constantinople fail against Greek fire. On his death Yazid demands allegiance; Husayn, the Prophet's (PBUH) grandson, refuses — and is martyred with his family at Karbala, 680: a wound in Muslim memory to this day, treated here with the gravity it demands.","meanwhile":"Tang China at maximum extent; the Bulgars cross the Danube founding Bulgaria (681).","pop":null,"src":"al-Tabari v.18–19 · al-Bidayah v.6 · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"32","num":"32","side":"i","sort":705,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"685–715 CE","ah":"66–96 AH","title":"Abd al-Malik and al-Walid — an empire on three continents","map":"700","panel":"p6","pins":[["Dome of the Rock, 691","Jerusalem",31.778,35.235],["Gibraltar 711 — Jabal Tariq","Strait of Gibraltar",36.14,-5.35],["Sindh 711 — Muhammad bin Qasim","Debal / Karachi region",24.86,67.01],["Bukhara & Samarqand — Qutayba","Transoxiana",39.65,66.96]],"story":"After the second civil war (fitna), Abd al-Malik institutionalizes: Arabic becomes the administrative language; the first Islamic coinage — gold dinar, silver dirham (~697) — replaces Byzantine and Persian money; the Dome of the Rock rises. Under al-Walid, 711 is the year of wonders: Tariq crosses into Spain, Muhammad bin Qasim lands in Sindh, Qutayba drives into Bukhara and Samarqand. Three continents, one color, for the first time in history — the largest empire the world had yet seen.","meanwhile":"Nara becomes Japan's first capital (710); the second Arab siege of Constantinople (717–718) fails, fixing the frontier; Tours (732) checks a raiding column in France.","pop":"World ~210M · the caliphate ~30–35M","src":"al-Bidayah v.6 · al-Tabari v.21–23 · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"33","num":"33","side":"i","sort":718,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"717–720 CE","ah":"99–101 AH","title":"Umar II — two years that became the benchmark","map":"700","panel":"p6","pins":[["Capital: Damascus","Damascus",33.51,36.29]],"story":"Two and a half years remembered as a golden interlude: confiscated wealth returned, cursing from pulpits ended, scholars sent where soldiers had gone, the first official hadith compilation ordered — and the welfare tax (zakat) collectors in some districts unable to find poor people to receive it: Islamic history's own benchmark of just governance.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"al-Bidayah v.6 · Sarwat Saulat v.1"},{"id":"34","num":"34","side":"i","sort":750,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"750 CE","ah":"132 AH","title":"The Abbasid Revolution","map":"800","panel":"p6","pins":[["Black banners from Khurasan","Merv, Turkmenistan",37.66,62.19],["The Zab — the Umayyads fall","Great Zab river, Iraq",36.0,43.4],["One prince escapes to Spain","Cordoba",37.88,-4.78]],"story":"Grievances of non-Arab Muslims, Kharijite (extremist splinter) revolts and Hashimite claims converge; black banners sweep west; the Umayyads are destroyed at the Zab. One prince — Abd al-Rahman — crosses North Africa to Spain and founds the emirate of Cordoba (756): from now on the map shows more than one Muslim state, permanently.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"al-Tabari v.27 · Sarwat Saulat v.2"},{"id":"35","num":"35","side":"i","sort":790,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"762–809 CE","ah":"145–193 AH","title":"Baghdad and Harun al-Rashid — the golden age opens","map":"800","panel":"p6","pins":[["The round City of Peace, 762","Baghdad",33.31,44.36],["Talas 751 — paper leaves China","Talas river, Kyrgyzstan/Kazakhstan",42.52,72.23],["An elephant to Charlemagne","Aachen, Germany",50.78,6.08]],"story":"Al-Mansur founds Baghdad at the trade crossroads; within decades it may be Earth's largest city. Harun al-Rashid: embassies to Charlemagne (an elephant walks from Baghdad to Aachen) and Tang China. The hinge: papermakers captured at Talas (751) — paper mills in Samarqand, then Baghdad; books become cheap; the House of Wisdom translates Greek, Persian and Indian science. Al-Khwarizmi's algebra, Jabir's chemistry, the four schools of law (madhhabs) crystallizing, al-Bukhari and Muslim compiling — all in this arc.","meanwhile":"Charlemagne crowned (800); Vikings hit Lindisfarne (793) and will trade Abbasid silver up the Volga; the An Lushan rebellion breaks Tang China's noon; the Maya collapse begins.","pop":"World ~220–250M · Baghdad, Cordoba, Chang'an: the three megacities","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.2 · al-Tabari v.28–34 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"36","num":"36","side":"i","sort":970,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"900s–1000s CE","ah":"4th c. AH","title":"One civilization, many states","map":"1000","panel":"p7","pins":[["Caliphate of Cordoba, 929","Cordoba, Spain",37.88,-4.78],["Cairo founded 969; al-Azhar 970","Cairo, Egypt",30.04,31.24],["Ibn Fadlan's embassy north, 922","Volga Bulgaria",55.0,49.3],["Islam by trade: the Swahili coast","Kilwa, Tanzania",-8.96,39.51]],"story":"Political fragmentation, civilizational expansion: Cordoba proclaims its caliphate; the Fatimids found Cairo and al-Azhar; the Seljuk Turks take the caliph's protection; Mahmud raids deep into India — while Islam travels peacefully by trade to West Africa, the Swahili coast, the Volga and Southeast Asia. Ibn Sina's Canon becomes Europe's medical textbook for six centuries; Ibn al-Haytham founds experimental optics; al-Biruni measures the Earth.","meanwhile":"The Great Schism splits Christianity (1054); the Normans take England (1066); Song China invents paper money, movable type and the compass; Vikings touch Newfoundland (~1000).","pop":"World ~265M · Cordoba ~250–450K while Paris is a town","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.2 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"37","num":"37","side":"i","sort":1130,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1071–1187 CE","ah":"463–583 AH","title":"Seljuks, Crusades, Salahuddin","map":"1100","panel":"p7","pins":[["Manzikert 1071","Malazgirt, Turkey",39.15,42.54],["Jerusalem falls to the First Crusade, 1099","Al-Quds",31.78,35.23],["Hattin, 4 July 1187","Horns of Hattin, Galilee",32.8,35.45]],"story":"Manzikert shatters Byzantium's army — Anatolia begins becoming Turkey; Byzantium's call for help becomes the First Crusade, and Jerusalem falls in 1099 with a massacre both sides' chroniclers record. Zangi, Nur ad-Din, then Salahuddin: Egypt and Syria united, Hattin won, Jerusalem restored in 1187 — famously without a massacre; even European chroniclers made him chivalry's model. The Third Crusade ends at Ramla: coast to the Crusaders, Jerusalem stays Muslim with pilgrim access.","meanwhile":"The university is born in Europe (Bologna 1088) — largely translating Arabic science via Toledo; Angkor Wat rises in Cambodia.","pop":null,"src":"Sarwat Saulat v.2 · al-Bidayah v.7"},{"id":"38","num":"38","side":"i","sort":1258,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1258–1260 CE","ah":"656 AH","title":"The Mongol catastrophe — and the tide turned at Ain Goliath (Jalut)","map":"1279","panel":"p8","pins":[["Baghdad sacked, Feb 1258","Baghdad",33.31,44.36],["Ain Goliath (Jalut), 3 Sept 1260 — the tide stopped","Spring of Goliath, Palestine",32.55,35.35]],"story":"Genghis Khan's storm had already annihilated Khwarazm — Bukhara, Samarqand, Merv. His grandson Hulagu sacks Baghdad: the last Abbasid caliph killed, the House of Wisdom's books darkening the Tigris — classical historiography's blackest page; five centuries of Baghdad's caliphate end. Two years later the Mamluks of Egypt under Qutuz and Baybars stop the Mongols irreversibly at Ain Goliath (Jalut); Cairo becomes Islam's ark. Then the conquerors convert: the Ilkhans (1295) and the Golden Horde embrace the faith of the lands they broke.","meanwhile":"The Mongol Empire is history's largest contiguous realm — run by census, post-roads and terror; its peace reopens the Silk Road end to end.","pop":"The Mongol century costs tens of millions","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.2 · al-Bidayah v.7 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"39","num":"39","side":"i","sort":1330,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1260–1400s CE","ah":"7th–8th c. AH","title":"Mansa Musa, Ibn Battuta — and the Black Death","map":"1400","panel":"p8","pins":[["Acre 1291 — the last Crusader port","Akko",32.93,35.08],["Mansa Musa's golden pilgrimage (hajj), 1324","Timbuktu, Mali",16.77,-3.01],["Ibn Battuta sets out, 1325","Tangier, Morocco",35.76,-5.83],["Delhi Sultanate","Delhi",28.61,77.21]],"story":"The Mamluks expel the last Crusaders and guard the holy cities. Islam's centers multiply: the Delhi Sultanate; Mali — Mansa Musa's pilgrimage (hajj) scatters so much gold through Cairo that prices reportedly sag for years, and Timbuktu becomes a manuscript capital; the Ottoman beylik is born (1299). Ibn Battuta crosses the entire Muslim world, Morocco to China, on its own networks; Ibn Khaldun writes the Muqaddimah (1377). Then the Black Death (1347–51) kills perhaps a third of the lands from China to England.","meanwhile":"The Hundred Years' War; the Ming overthrow the Mongols (1368); Timur's last steppe empire sacks Delhi and nearly strangles the Ottomans at Ankara (1402); Zheng He's fleets — under a Muslim admiral — reach Africa.","pop":"World ~440M (1340) → ~360–375M (1400): the cliff","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.2–3 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"40","num":"40","side":"i","sort":1453,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"29 May 1453","ah":"857 AH","title":"Constantinople becomes Istanbul","map":"1492","panel":"p9","pins":[["The walls fall to Mehmed al-Fatih","Istanbul",41.01,28.98]],"story":"Mehmed II, aged 21, takes the city that repelled Islam for 800 years — giant cannon, ships hauled overland into the Golden Horn. The Roman Empire, fifteen centuries old, ends; Hagia Sophia becomes a mosque; the graves of the Prophet's (PBUH) companions from the 674 siege anchor the city's Islamic geography. Scholars fleeing west with Greek manuscripts feed the Renaissance — one event, two civilizational stories.","meanwhile":"Gutenberg's press begins printing in these very years (~1450–55): Europe gets cheap books just as it receives Greek learning.","pop":null,"src":"Sarwat Saulat v.3"},{"id":"41","num":"41","side":"i","sort":1492,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1492","ah":"897 AH","title":"Granada falls; Columbus sails","map":"1492","panel":"p9","pins":[["The last Muslim state of al-Andalus","Granada, Spain",37.18,-3.6],["Ottoman ships rescue the expelled","Istanbul",41.01,28.98]],"story":"After 781 years of Islamic Iberia, Granada surrenders; within months the same monarchs fund Columbus. Muslims and Jews face conversion or expulsion — many Sephardim find refuge in Ottoman lands; Bayezid II sends ships. The hinge of world history: the Old World's internal frontier closes and the Atlantic opens; the Americas enter the map as connected territory.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Sarwat Saulat v.3"},{"id":"42","num":"42","side":"i","sort":1517,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1517","ah":"923 AH","title":"The caliphate passes to the Ottomans","map":"1530","panel":"p9","pins":[["Selim I takes Cairo","Cairo",30.04,31.24],["Custodianship of the Haramayn","Mecca & Madinah",21.42,39.83],["The same year: Wittenberg","Wittenberg, Germany",51.87,12.65]],"story":"Selim I defeats the Safavids at Chaldiran and conquers the Mamluk empire; custodianship of Mecca and Madinah — and, per Ottoman tradition, the caliphal title — pass to Istanbul until 1924. The same year, Luther posts his theses: the caliphate consolidates in the east as Western Christendom fractures. Three gunpowder empires now hold the Muslim world: Ottomans, Safavids (Iran forcibly Shia from 1501 — the Sunni-Shia map hardens), and the Mughals from 1526 — the wealthiest realm on Earth.","meanwhile":null,"pop":"Mughal India ~100–150M — about a quarter of world GDP by ~1700","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.3"},{"id":"43","num":"43","side":"i","sort":1529,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1520–1566","ah":"926–974 AH","title":"Suleiman the Lawgiver","map":"1530","panel":"p9","pins":[["First siege of Vienna, 1529","Vienna, Austria",48.21,16.37],["Sinan's Istanbul","Istanbul",41.01,28.98]],"story":"Belgrade, Rhodes, Mohacs — Hungary falls — then the gates of Vienna; Barbarossa's fleet rules the Mediterranean; alliance with France crosses religious lines; the Kanun law code; Sinan's mosques define a skyline. Istanbul, at ~600–700 thousand, is Europe's largest city.","meanwhile":"Cortes takes Tenochtitlan (1521), Pizarro the Inca (1533) — American silver begins flooding the world economy; Magellan's crew circles the globe; Copernicus publishes; Ivan the Terrible takes Muslim Kazan (1552) — Russia's 350-year push south begins.","pop":"World ~545–580M by 1600","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.3 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"44","num":"44","side":"i","sort":1690,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1600s–1798","ah":"11th–12th c. AH","title":"The slow reversal","map":"1700","panel":"p10","pins":[["Vienna 1683 — the failed second siege","Vienna",48.21,16.37],["Karlowitz 1699 — the first retreat","Sremski Karlovci, Serbia",45.2,19.93],["Plassey 1757 — the Company takes Bengal","Palashi, India",23.8,88.25],["Napoleon lands in Egypt, 1798","Alexandria",31.2,29.92]],"story":"The pattern the map shows: Islamic states stay vast, but dynamism migrates. Vienna fails (1683); Karlowitz (1699) signs away Hungary — the first backward morph. Safavid Isfahan dazzles, then falls (1722); the Mughals decay after Aurangzeb — and the East India Company, after Plassey (1757), rules more Indians than the emperor. Russia annexes Crimea (1783) — the first Muslim-majority land taken by a European power in the modern era. In 1798 Napoleon lands in Egypt: Europe now projects power into the heartland at will.","meanwhile":"The scientific revolution (Newton 1687); the Atlantic slave trade at its horrific peak; American and French revolutions; steam engines turning in Britain — the industrial gap opens.","pop":"World ~900M–1B by 1800; the billion crossed ~1804","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.3–4 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"45","num":"45","side":"i","sort":1860,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1800s","ah":"13th c. AH","title":"The colonization of the Muslim world","map":"1880","panel":"p11","pins":[["France takes Algeria, 1830","Algiers",36.75,3.06],["1857 — the last Mughal exiled","Delhi",28.61,77.21],["Suez Canal, 1869","Suez, Egypt",30.59,32.27],["Britain occupies Egypt, 1882","Cairo",30.04,31.24],["Russia takes Tashkent, 1865","Tashkent",41.3,69.24],["Berlin Conference, 1884–85","Berlin",52.52,13.4]],"story":"Region by region: France in Algeria, Tunisia, Morocco; Britain ruling India directly after 1857 — the Mughal line ends in a Rangoon exile; Egypt occupied after Suez made it the world's hinge; Russia absorbing the Caucasus and Central Asia; the Dutch in Indonesia; and at Berlin (1884–85), Africa's borders drawn with rulers and pencils — the most consequential map-redrawing this site shows. Ottoman responses: Tanzimat reforms, the 1876 constitution, Abdulhamid II's pan-Islamism and the Hijaz Railway (1908).","meanwhile":"Railways, telegraphs and steamships shrink the planet; London (6.5M) is Earth's largest city — the population map centers on Europe for the first time in this whole timeline.","pop":"World ~1.6B by 1900","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.4–5 · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"46","num":"46","side":"i","sort":1916,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1914–1918","ah":"1332–1337 AH","title":"World War I — the caliphate's last war","map":"1914","panel":"p12","pins":[["Gallipoli, 1915","Gelibolu, Turkey",40.41,26.67],["Sykes–Picot lines, 1916","Levant",34.0,38.0],["Jerusalem surrenders, Dec 1917","Al-Quds",31.78,35.23]],"story":"The Ottomans enter on Germany's side; the caliph proclaims jihad, but the age of dynastic legitimacy is over. Gallipoli is the last great Ottoman victory. Britain plays three hands at once — the McMahon–Hussein promises of Arab independence, the secret Sykes–Picot partition, and the Balfour Declaration — three documents whose contradictions still shape the map. The Arab Revolt takes Aqaba and Damascus; the empire capitulates at Mudros (1918).","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Sarwat Saulat v.5"},{"id":"47","num":"47","side":"i","sort":1924,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"3 March 1924","ah":"1342 AH","title":"The caliphate is abolished","map":"1920","panel":"p13","pins":[["The Grand National Assembly's vote","Ankara",39.93,32.86],["The last caliph boards the Orient Express","Istanbul",41.01,28.98],["Mandates carve the Arab lands","Damascus / Baghdad / Jerusalem",33.5,36.3]],"story":"Out of defeat, the Turkish national movement wins its war and its republic (1923); on 3 March 1924 the assembly abolishes the caliphate — Abdulmejid II, the 101st successor of an institution founded at Saqifah in 632, goes into exile. After 1,292 years: no caliph. India's Khilafat Movement had mobilized millions to save it; its failure redirects Muslim politics toward what becomes Pakistan. The map transformation of 1920–24 is this site's centerpiece: mandates (British Iraq, Transjordan, Palestine; French Syria, Lebanon), Saudi consolidation of Arabia (kingdom, 1932), and the modern Middle Eastern borders appearing in a single frame.","meanwhile":null,"pop":null,"src":"Sarwat Saulat v.5"},{"id":"48","num":"48","side":"i","sort":1932,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1924–1939","ah":"1343–1358 AH","title":"A world without a caliph","map":"1930","panel":"p13","pins":[["Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, 1932","Riyadh",24.71,46.68],["Oil struck at Dammam, 1938","Dammam",26.43,50.1],["The Muslim Brotherhood founded, 1928","Ismailia, Egypt",30.6,32.27],["The Pakistan idea, 1930–40","Lahore",31.55,74.34]],"story":"The Muslim world reorganizes: Saudi Arabia proclaimed and oil discovered — the pin that will re-weight the region; Turkey secularizes (new alphabet, 1928); Iran modernizes by decree; the Brotherhood (1928) and the Pakistan movement (Iqbal 1930; Lahore Resolution 1940) set the century's two templates — Islamist movement and Muslim nation-state; Mandate Palestine sees rising immigration and the 1936–39 revolt.","meanwhile":"The Depression breaks the world economy; totalitarianisms rise; Japan invades Manchuria, then China.","pop":null,"src":"Sarwat Saulat v.5"},{"id":"49","num":"49","side":"i","sort":1943,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1939–1945","ah":"1358–1364 AH","title":"World War II — and the 1945 map","map":"1938","panel":"p13","pins":[["El Alamein, 1942","El Alamein, Egypt",30.83,28.95],["Anglo-Soviet occupation of Iran, 1941","Tehran",35.69,51.39],["The UN founded, 1945","San Francisco",37.77,-122.42]],"story":"The deadliest event in human history — some 70–85 million dead. Muslim lands are battlefields and manpower: North Africa, occupied Iran, 2.5 million Indian volunteers — the largest volunteer army ever raised. The Holocaust murders six million Jews in Europe — stated plainly, as this site's rules require. The closing frame: Europe's empires bankrupt, the UN founded with Egypt, Iraq, Iran, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Lebanon and Turkey among founders, two superpowers standing — and decolonization loaded: Indonesia declares independence in the very month the war ends. The map fades from 1945 toward today's borders, closing the loop on the founding question: where was this place, what was it called then, and what is it called now?","meanwhile":null,"pop":"World ~2.3B","src":"Sarwat Saulat v.5 · HYDE / Our World in Data"},{"id":"W1","num":"W1","side":"w","sort":-3300,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~3500–3000 BC","ah":null,"title":"Sumer & Egypt — writing, the wheel, the first cities","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Uruk — plausibly Earth's first city","Warka, Iraq",31.32,45.64],["Egypt unified under one crown","Nile valley",26.0,32.0]],"story":"Cuneiform begins as accounting — history literally starts as bookkeeping; the wheel, the plow, bronze; Narmer unifies Egypt (~3100 BC).","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the undated generations between Adam and Noah (peace be upon him); tradition places Enoch (peace be upon him) — first to write with the pen — in exactly this dawn-of-writing world.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"W2","num":"W2","side":"w","sort":-2560,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~2560 BC","ah":null,"title":"The Great Pyramid of Giza","map":"bc3000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Khufu's pyramid","Giza, Egypt",29.98,31.13]],"story":"The heaviest building ever raised; tallest structure on Earth for ~3,800 years. Built by rotating paid labor crews — excavated bread-and-beer rations — not by Israelite slaves, who belong over a millennium later.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the undated era before Abraham (peace be upon him).","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W3","num":"W3","side":"w","sort":-2300,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~2600–1900 BC","ah":null,"title":"The Indus Valley civilization","map":"bc2000","panel":"p1","pins":[["Mohenjo-daro","Sindh, Pakistan",27.33,68.14],["Harappa","Punjab, Pakistan",30.63,72.87]],"story":"Planned street grids, standardized bricks and weights, household drainage unmatched until Rome — and an undeciphered script guarding its thoughts. Its quiet decline remains debated.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: era of Abraham (peace be upon him) — while he journeys Ur to Mecca, the Indus cities are already old.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"W4","num":"W4","side":"w","sort":-1770,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~1792–1750 BC","ah":null,"title":"Hammurabi's Babylon","map":"bc2000","panel":"p1","pins":[["The law-code stele","Babylon, Iraq",32.54,44.42]],"story":"282 judgments carved in diorite — “so the strong shall not harm the weak” — with class-graded penalties showing both the ideal and its limits.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: within roughly a century of Ibrahim's (peace be upon him) debate with a Babylonian tyrant (Q 2:258) — display the stele beside the Quranic scene.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Q 2:258"},{"id":"W5","num":"W5","side":"w","sort":-1200,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~1200–1150 BC","ah":null,"title":"The Bronze Age Collapse","map":"bc1000","panel":"p2","pins":[["Mycenae burns","Greece",37.73,22.76],["Hattusa abandoned","Boğazkale, Turkey",40.02,34.62]],"story":"Within fifty years: Mycenae burns, the Hittite Empire vanishes, Egypt barely repels the Sea Peoples, trade and literacy crash — the ancient world's system failure. Iron rises from the wreckage.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: decades after the era of Moses (peace be upon him); the Children of Israel (Bani Israil) are in Canaan under Joshua (peace be upon him).","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W6","num":"W6","side":"w","sort":-880,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"911–609 BC","ah":null,"title":"The Assyrian war machine","map":"bc700","panel":"p3","pins":[["Nineveh & Ashurbanipal's library","Mosul, Iraq",36.36,43.15]],"story":"History's first true empire of provinces, standing armies, siege engineering, mass deportation — and the library that preserved Mesopotamia's literature. It ends with Nineveh's own destruction (612 BC).","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: Jonah (peace be upon him) is sent to this empire's giant capital (entry 12); Ilyas and Elisha (peace be upon him) preach in its shadow.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Q 37:147"},{"id":"W7","num":"W7","side":"w","sort":-586,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"586 BC","ah":null,"title":"Nebuchadnezzar destroys the First Temple","map":"bc500","panel":"p3","pins":[["Neo-Babylon — Ishtar Gate","Babylon",32.54,44.42],["The Temple burned; the exile","Jerusalem",31.78,35.23]],"story":"Neo-Babylon at its height destroys Sulayman's (peace be upon him) Temple and exiles the Judeans — the exile that reshapes the Children of Israel (Bani Israil)'s scripture and identity. Classical commentators connect it to the first “corruption” of Q 17:4–7.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: era of the later Israelite prophets; Daniel (Danyal), honored in Islamic tradition, among the exiles.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Q 17:4–7 · al-Bidayah v.2"},{"id":"W8","num":"W8","side":"w","sort":-550,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"550–330 BC","ah":null,"title":"Cyrus & the Persian Empire","map":"bc500","panel":"p3","pins":[["Pasargadae — Cyrus's capital","Fars, Iran",30.2,53.17],["Persepolis","Fars, Iran",29.93,52.89]],"story":"The first state spanning three continents' edges — satrapies, the Royal Road, and a policy of restoring exiled peoples (the Cyrus Cylinder: over-celebrated as a “rights charter,” genuinely a landmark of imperial tolerance). Cyrus returns the Judean exiles to rebuild Jerusalem.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: many later Muslim scholars argue Cyrus fits Dhul-Qarnayn (entry 12b) — a just world-king traveling east and west; the debate itself is content.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Q 18:83–98"},{"id":"W9","num":"W9","side":"w","sort":-520,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~600–450 BC","ah":null,"title":"The Axial Age — the world thinks at once","map":"bc500","panel":"p3","pins":[["Buddha — the Ganges plain","Bodh Gaya, India",24.7,84.99],["Confucius — Lu state","Qufu, China",35.6,116.99],["First philosophers","Miletus & Athens",37.53,27.28]],"story":"Across disconnected civilizations in a few generations — Buddha, Confucius, Laozi, the Greek philosophers, Zoroaster (dating debated) — humanity's enduring ethical systems appear. Historians still argue why.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the Quran's own frame — “there was no nation but that a warner had passed within it” (Q 35:24).","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Q 35:24"},{"id":"W10","num":"W10","side":"w","sort":-450,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"508–322 BC","ah":null,"title":"Classical Greece","map":"bc500","panel":"p3","pins":[["Athens — democracy & the Academy","Athens",37.98,23.73]],"story":"Athenian democracy (male citizens only — a fifth of residents: honesty first), the Persian Wars, the Parthenon, Socrates executed by the democracy, Plato, Aristotle, Hippocrates' oath — the corpus Baghdad's House of Wisdom will translate twelve centuries later.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: draw the arrow across time to entry 35 — Athens to Baghdad.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W11","num":"W11","side":"w","sort":-330,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"336–323 BC","ah":null,"title":"Alexander & the Hellenistic world","map":"bc323","panel":"p3","pins":[["From Macedon to the Indus","Pella → Punjab",40.76,22.52],["Alexandria founded, 331 BC","Alexandria, Egypt",31.2,29.92]],"story":"Thirteen years, the Persian empire swallowed, seventy cities founded; Greek becomes the lingua franca from Egypt to Bactria; the Library rises under his successors.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: classical commentators often identified Alexander with Dhul-Qarnayn; later scholars objected to his paganism — both candidacies at entry 12b.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · al-Bidayah v.2"},{"id":"W12","num":"W12","side":"w","sort":-250,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"268–232 BC","ah":null,"title":"Ashoka's India","map":"bc200","panel":"p3","pins":[["Edicts on rock and pillar","Patna (Pataliputra), India",25.61,85.14]],"story":"After the bloodbath of Kalinga, the Mauryan emperor carves remorse and welfare policy across the subcontinent — hospitals, wells, tolerance: antiquity's most explicit governance-by-conscience; his missions carry Buddhism abroad.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: undated interval; the Q 35:24 frame applies.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W13","num":"W13","side":"w","sort":-210,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"221 BC – 220 CE","ah":null,"title":"China unified — Qin & Han","map":"bc200","panel":"p4","pins":[["The First Emperor's capital","Xi'an (Xianyang)",34.34,108.94],["The Silk Road opens west","Dunhuang gate",40.14,94.66]],"story":"Qin standardizes script, weights, axle-widths, walls — and burns dissenting books. Han follows: the exam ideal, paper (~105 CE), and Zhang Qian's missions opening the Silk Road.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: runs into the era of Jesus (peace be upon him) — Han and Rome are the twin superpowers bracketing his world (entry 13).","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"W14","num":"W14","side":"w","sort":-100,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"264–27 BC","ah":null,"title":"Rome rises","map":"bc1","panel":"p4","pins":[["Rome","Rome, Italy",41.89,12.48],["Carthage erased, 146 BC","Tunis, Tunisia",36.85,10.32]],"story":"Punic Wars — Hannibal's elephants over the Alps, Carthage erased — then the Republic devours the Mediterranean and itself: Caesar, civil wars, Augustus (27 BC). Roman law, roads and citizenship build the stage onto which Jesus (peace be upon him) is born.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: leads directly into entry 13.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W15","num":"W15","side":"w","sort":380,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"312–476 CE","ah":null,"title":"Rome turns Christian — then falls in the West","map":"400","panel":"p4","pins":[["Constantinople founded, 330","Istanbul",41.01,28.98],["Nicaea, 325","İznik, Turkey",40.43,29.72],["Rome ends in the West, 476","Rome",41.89,12.48]],"story":"Constantine legalizes Christianity and chairs Nicaea — the creed-fixing the Quran later addresses (Q 4:171); Theodosius makes it the state religion; the West collapses into Germanic kingdoms while Byzantium carries on a thousand years.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the heart of the long gap (fatrah) (entry 14); the People of the Cave (14b) sleep across precisely this transformation.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Q 4:171"},{"id":"W16","num":"W16","side":"w","sort":430,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"~320–550 CE","ah":null,"title":"Gupta India's golden age","map":"400","panel":"p4","pins":[["Zero, decimals, Aryabhata","Patna (Pataliputra)",25.61,85.14],["Nalanda university","Bihar, India",25.14,85.44]],"story":"Zero as a number, the decimal system, Aryabhata computing pi and Earth's rotation, Nalanda rising. The numerals the world writes today traveled India → Baghdad (al-Khwarizmi) → Europe as “Arabic numerals.”","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the long gap (fatrah) (entry 14) — and one of the site's best cross-track arrows, into entry 35.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W18","num":"W18","side":"w","sort":700,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"618–907 CE","ah":null,"title":"Tang China — the other superpower","map":"700","panel":"p6","pins":[["Chang'an — a million people","Xi'an, China",34.34,108.94],["Muslim merchants settle Canton","Guangzhou",23.13,113.26]],"story":"Founded four years before the migration to Madinah (the Hijrah); the world's most cosmopolitan capital, with mosques, churches and fire-temples on its avenues; embassies exchanged with the caliphs; broken at its noon by the An Lushan rebellion (755–63). Islam reaches China by sea in its first century.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: Parts II–V run parallel; Talas (751, entry 35) touches the two worlds together.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Sarwat Saulat v.2"},{"id":"W20","num":"W20","side":"w","sort":900,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"793–1066 CE","ah":null,"title":"The Viking Age","map":"900","panel":"p6","pins":[["Lindisfarne raided, 793","Northumbria, England",55.68,-1.8],["Dirhams up the Volga — the Rus","Volga route",56.0,44.0],["Leif Erikson → Vinland ~1000","Newfoundland",51.6,-55.5]],"story":"Raiders become traders and state-founders: the Rus give Russia its name and row down the Volga to trade furs for Abbasid dirhams — Ibn Fadlan's 922 embassy is the classic eyewitness account; Normandy (911), England (1066), America touched (~1000).","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the Abbasid golden age (entries 35–36) — Swedish soil still yields Abbasid silver: the two tracks physically touching.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Sarwat Saulat v.2"},{"id":"W22","num":"W22","side":"w","sort":1215,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1215","ah":null,"title":"Magna Carta","map":"1200","panel":"p7","pins":[["Runnymede","Surrey, England",51.44,-0.56]],"story":"Rebel barons force King John to concede the crown sits under law — a narrow feudal document that grows into a constitutional myth with real consequences.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: paired honestly with the Islamic law-state ideal (Panel 6) — two civilizations reaching “the ruler is not above the law” by different routes; between the Crusades (37) and the Mongols (38).","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W24","num":"W24","side":"w","sort":1440,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1325–1533","ah":null,"title":"The American empires — Aztec & Inca","map":"1492","panel":"p9","pins":[["Tenochtitlan — the lake city","Mexico City",19.43,-99.13],["Cusco & the 40,000-km road net","Cusco, Peru",-13.53,-71.97]],"story":"Tenochtitlan: causeways and floating gardens, 200,000+ people — larger than contemporary Paris; the Inca run an empire on roads and khipu cord-accounting without writing or wheels. Both fall (1521, 1533) to steel, horses, smallpox and local allies.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: the Ottoman rise and the 1492 hinge (entries 40–42) — the map gains a hemisphere exactly here.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"W25","num":"W25","side":"w","sort":1475,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1440–1543","ah":null,"title":"Print, Renaissance, Copernicus","map":"1492","panel":"p9","pins":[["Gutenberg's press, ~1450","Mainz, Germany",50.0,8.27],["Copernicus moves the Earth, 1543","Frombork, Poland",54.36,19.68]],"story":"Cheap books arrive exactly as Constantinople's fall pushes Greek scholars west; Leonardo and Michelangelo work as Sinan builds for the Ottomans; Copernicus publishes.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: entries 40–42; the honest paired card on Arabic-script printing's late start lives at Panel 9.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W26","num":"W26","side":"w","sort":1640,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1517–1648","ah":null,"title":"Reformation → Westphalia: the bordered map is born","map":"1650","panel":"p10","pins":[["Luther's theses, 1517","Wittenberg",51.87,12.65],["The Peace of Westphalia, 1648","Münster & Osnabrück",51.96,7.63]],"story":"A century of confessional war kills perhaps a third of Germany and ends at Westphalia — the treaty credited with the sovereign territorial state: the very idea that the world is a jigsaw of hard-bordered states, which is the visual grammar of this entire website. Before this, most of the map you've been watching ran on overlapping allegiances, not lines.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: Ottoman noon and slow reversal (entries 42–44).","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W28","num":"W28","side":"w","sort":1776,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1687–1804","ah":null,"title":"Scientific revolution & the age of revolutions","map":"1783","panel":"p11","pins":[["Newton's Principia, 1687","London",51.51,-0.13],["1776","Philadelphia",39.95,-75.17],["1789","Paris",48.86,2.35],["Haiti — the slave revolution that won","Port-au-Prince",18.54,-72.34]],"story":"Enlightenment rights-language; America and France proclaim liberty while slavery persists — the contradiction stated without varnish; Haiti (1791–1804), history's only successful slave revolution, calls the bluff and wins.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: entry 44 — the same decades as Plassey and the Company's rise in India.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W29","num":"W29","side":"w","sort":1850,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1760–1871","ah":null,"title":"Industry, abolition, unifications, Meiji","map":"1880","panel":"p11","pins":[["Manchester — the first industrial city","Manchester, England",53.48,-2.24],["Meiji Restoration, 1868","Tokyo",35.68,139.69]],"story":"Steam, coal and factories open the Great Divergence; Britain abolishes the trade (1807) and slavery (1833); the US Civil War ends in abolition (1865); Germany and Italy unify; Meiji Japan proves a non-European state can industrialize on its own terms — studied intently by Ottoman and Egyptian reformers.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: entry 45 — precisely the decades the colonial map floods over the Muslim world.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Sarwat Saulat v.4–5"},{"id":"W31","num":"W31","side":"w","sort":1917,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1917","ah":null,"title":"The Russian Revolution","map":"1914","panel":"p12","pins":[["The Tsar falls; the USSR rises","St. Petersburg (Petrograd)",59.94,30.31]],"story":"The empire ruling more Muslims than the Ottoman sultan collapses into the Soviet Union; Central Asia's mosques face an atheist state; the USSR becomes one pole of the world the 1945 frame inherits.","meanwhile":"Prophetic line: entries 46–47 — the Romanovs and the Ottoman caliphate end within six years of each other.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Sarwat Saulat v.5"},{"id":"W17","num":"W17","side":"w","sort":600,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"602–628 CE","ah":null,"title":"The last great war of antiquity","map":"600","panel":"p5","pins":[["Constantinople besieged","Istanbul, Turkey",41.01,28.98],["Persia's capital","Ctesiphon → Salman Pak, Iraq",33.09,44.58]],"story":"Rome's eastern empire (Byzantium) and Persia fight for twenty-six years — the longest and most exhausting war of the ancient world. Persia takes Syria, Jerusalem and Egypt; Byzantium is nearly finished; then Heraclius counter-attacks and wins it all back by 628. Both empires end the war bankrupt, depopulated and hollow — which is why, within a decade, neither can hold its frontier.","meanwhile":"Across the track: this is the exact backdrop of Muhammad's (PBUH) mission (entries 15–26). The Quran comments on the war as it happens (30:1–5), predicting Rome's comeback while Rome is losing.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · Quran 30:1–5"},{"id":"W19","num":"W19","side":"w","sort":805,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"768–814 CE","ah":null,"title":"Charlemagne and the revival of the West","map":"800","panel":"p6","pins":[["Crowned Emperor, 800","Rome",41.89,12.48],["His capital","Aachen, Germany",50.78,6.08]],"story":"A Frankish king reunites much of western Europe and is crowned Emperor in Rome on Christmas Day, 800 — the West's first attempt to rebuild something Roman. His scholars invent the clear lowercase handwriting that this sentence still uses. Europe at this moment is rural, small and poor by comparison with Baghdad, Cordoba or Chang'an.","meanwhile":"Across the track: Harun al-Rashid's Baghdad (entry 35) exchanges embassies with him — an elephant named Abul-Abbas walks from Iraq to Germany as a diplomatic gift.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W21","num":"W21","side":"w","sort":1050,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"960–1279 CE","ah":null,"title":"Song China — the most advanced society on earth","map":"1100","panel":"p7","pins":[["Kaifeng — a city of a million","Kaifeng, China",34.8,114.31],["Hangzhou","Hangzhou, China",30.27,120.15]],"story":"Song China invents printing with movable type, the magnetic compass, paper money and gunpowder; its iron output will not be matched by Britain until about 1700; officials are chosen by written examination rather than birth. For roughly three centuries, China and the Muslim world are the two most sophisticated civilisations on the planet, and Europe is the periphery.","meanwhile":"Across the track: the same centuries as Cordoba, Cairo and the Persian literary renaissance (entries 36–37). Chinese paper reached Baghdad in 751, and Chinese porcelain filled Baghdad's markets.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W23","num":"W23","side":"w","sort":1348,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1347–1351","ah":null,"title":"The Black Death","map":"1400","panel":"p8","pins":[["Arrives at Caffa, then Europe","Feodosia, Crimea",45.03,35.38],["Cairo devastated","Cairo",30.04,31.24]],"story":"A plague travelling the trade roads kills perhaps a third of everyone from China to Morocco to England within four years — the deadliest event of the whole timeline until the twentieth century. Whole villages vanish; labour becomes scarce and, for the survivors, wages rise — one of history's grimmest economic lessons.","meanwhile":"Across the track: it strikes the Muslim world just as hard — Ibn Battuta was travelling through it, and Cairo lost a third of its people (entry 39). World population falls from about 440 million to about 370 million.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia · McEvedy & Jones"},{"id":"W27","num":"W27","side":"w","sort":1650,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1500–1867","ah":null,"title":"The Atlantic slave trade","map":"1650","panel":"p10","pins":[["Ships depart West Africa","Ouidah, Benin",6.36,2.09],["Sugar and death in the Caribbean","Barbados",13.19,-59.54],["The market in Brazil","Salvador, Brazil",-12.97,-38.5]],"story":"Roughly twelve million Africans are shipped across the Atlantic in chains to work sugar, tobacco and cotton; nearly two million die at sea. It is the largest forced migration in human history, and the engine of Europe's wealth in this period. No civilisation of the age is innocent of slavery — but this system's scale, its racial basis and its industrial cruelty make it, by this timeline's honest reckoning, the gravest crime of the modern era.","meanwhile":"Across the track: the same centuries as the Ottoman, Safavid and Mughal noon (entries 42–44) — empires that also held slaves, and that this site does not excuse.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"},{"id":"W30","num":"W30","side":"w","sort":1916,"dated":true,"yearLabel":"1914–1918","ah":null,"title":"The First World War in Europe","map":"1914","panel":"p12","pins":[["The trenches of the Western Front","Somme, France",50.0,2.65],["Empires fall","Vienna",48.21,16.37]],"story":"Industrial slaughter on a scale no one imagined: around seventeen million dead. Four empires — German, Austro-Hungarian, Russian and Ottoman — do not survive it. The world that emerges is one of nation-states, drawn on maps by exhausted victors.","meanwhile":"Across the track: the same war ends the caliphate's political life (entries 46–47). The lines drawn by Sykes and Picot in 1916 are still on today's map.","pop":null,"src":"World History Encyclopedia"}],"panels":{"p1":{"title":"~2000 BC — Era of Abraham (peace be upon him)","languages":"Sumerian fading to liturgy; Akkadian the diplomatic lingua franca; Egyptian hieroglyphs; the undeciphered Indus script. No alphabet exists yet anywhere.","money":"No coins on Earth — silver by weight (the shekel is a weight), barley as small change, barter elsewhere.","society":"Temple-and-palace economies; god-king absolutism (Nimrod's claim in Q 2:258 is the era's ideology verbatim); slavery ubiquitous; patriarchal clans.","politics":"City-states (Ur, Babylon, Mari) and the first territorial kingdoms; Middle Kingdom Egypt centralized under Pharaoh.","economy":"Donkey caravans Ashur–Anatolia (history's first business letters); Dilmun (Bahrain) linking Mesopotamia to the Indus by sea.","moral":"Gravest: institutional slavery, debt-bondage, god-kings. Most equitable: the law codes — Ur-Nammu (~2100 BC, oldest surviving) and Hammurabi, protecting “the widow and the orphan,” though justice was graded by class. Ibrahim's (peace be upon him) one-God, no-god-kings message was the era's radical moral claim.","wonders":"Ziggurats of Ur; Karnak begun; Stonehenge complete; Indus street-grid sanitation unmatched for millennia."},"p2":{"title":"~1250 BC — Era of Moses (peace be upon him)","languages":"Akkadian still the diplomatic tongue (the Amarna letters); Egyptian; Hittite; Mycenaean Greek; Chinese emerging on oracle bones — and in Sinai's mines, the Proto-Canaanite alphabet: ancestor of nearly every alphabet on Earth, born in Musa's (peace be upon him) landscape.","money":"Still no coins; Egypt's copper deben weight; gold rings and grain as payment.","society":"Palace economies on corvée and slave labor — the Israelites' bondage (Q 28:4) is the system's dark heart; scribes privileged; Egyptian women could own property, unusually.","politics":"The great-powers club — Egypt, Hatti, Babylon, Assyria, Mycenae — exchanging royal letters; Pharaoh's self-deification (“I am your lord most high,” Q 79:24) is the court language of the age.","economy":"Mediterranean bulk trade (the Uluburun wreck: ten tons of copper); Nubian gold; the incense route forming in Arabia.","moral":"Gravest: state slavery and infanticide by decree (Q 2:49). Most equitable: the Kadesh treaty — the first surviving international peace treaty; Deir el-Medina's workers stage history's first recorded strike and win. The Torah at Sinai (Q 7:145) enters history as a comprehensive law of justice for a liberated slave people — the era's moral revolution.","wonders":"Abu Simbel; the Exodus remembered by three faiths; iron spreading from Anatolia."},"p3":{"title":"~1000 BC — Era of Dawud & Solomon (peace be upon him)","languages":"Hebrew and Canaanite dialects; the Phoenician alphabet spreading by trade — Greeks adopt it within two centuries; Aramaic beginning its thousand-year career.","money":"Still pre-coinage — the first true coins (Lydia) are ~350 years ahead; Phoenicians trade by silver weight.","society":"Tribal confederations crystallizing into kingdoms; the prophet-king model — power answerable to revelation (Q 38:26) — against ordinary sacral kingship.","politics":"Egypt weak, Assyria gathering; the united kingdom under Dawud and Solomon (peace be upon him) is the Levant's brief great power; Tyre's merchant councils.","economy":"Red Sea fleets and the Saba axis (Q 27) — the incense road in full operation; Tyrian purple; iron democratizing tools and war.","moral":"Gravest: Assyrian mass-deportation warfare taking shape; ubiquitous slavery. Most equitable: Islamic tradition holds Sulayman's (peace be upon him) reign as the benchmark of just, prosperous rule under God (Q 27); Zhou China simultaneously articulates the Mandate of Heaven — rulers forfeit legitimacy through injustice.","wonders":"The First Temple; the Marib dam watering Yemen (Q 34:15); Phoenicians reportedly circumnavigating Africa."},"p4":{"title":"~1 CE — Era of Jesus (peace be upon him)","languages":"Aramaic — the language Jesus (peace be upon him) spoke — lingua franca from Egypt to Persia; Koine Greek in the east; Latin in the west; Sanskrit; Classical Chinese.","money":"Coinage universal in the classical belt — denarius, drachm, Han cash; moneychangers' tables in the Temple courts.","society":"Roman Italy perhaps 30–40% enslaved; gladiatorial games as entertainment; caste codifying in India. Isa's (peace be upon him) ministry to the poor and the outcast confronts the order directly.","politics":"Two superpowers (Rome, Han) plus Parthia between; client kings like Herod as imperial management; citizenship a legal caste.","economy":"The Silk Road's first golden age — silk for denarii; monsoon sailing to India; Petra and Himyar tax the incense road.","moral":"Gravest: crucifixion as state terror; the slave economy; infant exposure normal in Rome — its later prophetic condemnation was a moral rupture. Most equitable (relative): Han's exam-fed bureaucracy; Rome's developing law-of-all-peoples. The true moral revolution is prophetic: Isa's (peace be upon him) call, and John (peace be upon him) fearless unto death.","wonders":"Roman roads and aqueducts; the Julian calendar; Teotihuacan's pyramids rising unknown to the Old World."},"p5":{"title":"622 CE — The Hijrah","languages":"Arabic — being fixed forever by the Quran at this exact moment; Greek, Middle Persian, Syriac, Coptic, Latin dissolving into Romance, Sanskrit, Chinese. Within a century Arabic is administered from the Atlantic to the Indus.","money":"Byzantine gold solidus and Sasanian silver drachm — the Quran names the dinar (3:75) and dirham (12:20); Arabia mints nothing yet.","society":"Pre-Islamic Arabia: honor code, blood-feud, usury, slavery, daughters buried alive — abolished by one unanswerable question (Q 81:8–9). Madinah's new order: brotherhood, the Constitution making one ummah with mutual defense, the welfare tax (zakat) as welfare, emancipation as virtue (Q 90:13).","politics":"Two exhausted empires — and between them, for the first time, an Arabian polity built on covenant rather than kinship.","economy":"Quraysh's two caravan seasons (Q 106); Madinah's date-and-grain oasis; the Prophet's (PBUH) market rules — no hoarding, honest weights (Q 83:1–3).","moral":"Gravest: the Byzantine–Sasanian war's devastation; Arabia's infanticide and feud culture. Most equitable: by 622's standards, the Madinah charter and the Farewell Sermon (632) — life, property, women's rights, usury abolished, “no Arab superior to a non-Arab except by piety” — the era's most explicit statement of human equality.","wonders":"Tang China founded (618) — the two most consequential polities of the millennium born four years apart; the Grand Canal just finished."},"p6":{"title":"~800 CE — The Abbasid Golden Age","languages":"Arabic is the world language of science, law and administration from Cordoba to Sindh; New Persian reborn in Arabic script; Greek retreating; Old Turkic on steppe stones.","money":"The Islamic dinar and dirham are the dollar of the age — dug up in Viking Sweden, coastal Kenya and China; the sakk (→ “cheque”) moves money Baghdad to Cordoba.","society":"Cosmopolitan cities mixing Arab, Persian, Turk, Jew, Christian; scholars as celebrities; charitable endowment (waqf) endowments funding hospitals, schools and wells. Honest note: slavery persisted — the Zanj plantation system in Iraq's marshes revolted for 14 years; Islam mitigated slavery (emancipation as virtue, the enslaved rising to rule) but no civilization of the age abolished it.","politics":"A law-state: judges (qadis) applying religious law (fiqh) developed by independent scholars — the ruler subject, at least in theory, to a law he does not author; the four schools of law (madhhabs) crystallize now.","economy":"Islam's “green revolution” — rice, sugar, cotton, citrus moving west with irrigation manuals; Basra–Canton sailings; Baghdad's markets stocking porcelain and amber.","moral":"Gravest: the Zanj slave system; succession bloodshed. Most equitable: Umar ibn Abd al-Aziz's reign (717–20) — the welfare tax (zakat) collectors unable to find the poor in some districts; free hospitals; protected non-Muslim subjects (dhimmis) protected in law — second-class by modern standards, yet with enforceable rights of life, property and worship at a time Europe offered minorities far less.","wonders":"Paper mills; the House of Wisdom; algebra; hospitals with wards, records and licensing; street-lit, paved Cordoba while Paris was mud."},"p7":{"title":"~1000 CE","languages":"Arabic at zenith; Persian's literary renaissance (the Shahnameh); Old English and Old French forming; Swahili emerging as Bantu-Arabic trade speech.","money":"Dinar and dirham standard west of India; Song China issues the world's first government paper money (1024) — four centuries before Europe dares.","society":"The Cairo Geniza reveals a Mediterranean of contracts and long-distance trust among Muslim and Jewish merchants; al-Andalus produces Ibn Hazm now, Maimonides soon — who flees the Almohads to serve Saladin's court: honesty cuts both ways. European serfdom binds; Song exams open the widest farm-to-office path on Earth.","politics":"Many Muslim states, one legal-scholarly civilization — three rival caliphs, yet one pilgrimage (hajj) and one scholarly network.","economy":"Trans-Saharan gold (Ghana taxes it); the Volga fur-and-silver route; Song iron output unmatched by Britain until ~1700.","moral":"Gravest: the Slavic slave trade feeding all Mediterranean powers — the word “slave” is born from “Slav” in this era; untouchability hardening in India. Most equitable (relative): Song meritocracy and famine granaries; Islamic law's married women owning property outright — English wives wait until 1870 for the same.","wonders":"Experimental optics (Ibn al-Haytham); the Earth measured to ~1% (al-Biruni); Vikings brush America and part again."},"p8":{"title":"~1258 CE — The Mongol Age","languages":"Persian becomes the courtly lingua franca of the Turco-Mongol east; Arabic holds law and scripture; Mongolian decrees ride the yam post-relay; Middle English emerging.","money":"Mongol khanates try Chinese-style paper money — the Ilkhan's 1294 forced issue in Tabriz collapses markets in days: the Islamic world's first hyperinflation-by-decree; war debases the dirham.","society":"The Mamluk paradox — enslaved boys trained, freed and elevated until one rules Egypt: the age's strangest social ladder. Mongol law enforces religious tolerance while Mongol war annihilates cities.","politics":"History's largest contiguous empire, run by census, post-roads and terror — then its western khanates convert to Islam: law and faith absorbing the conqueror.","economy":"The Pax Mongolica reopens the Silk Road end to end — Marco Polo east, Ibn Battuta everywhere — and the same roads carry the Black Death west (1347).","moral":"Gravest: the Mongol massacres — Merv, Nishapur, Baghdad — described by contemporaries as civilization-ending; Crusade-era atrocities on both sides. Most equitable (relative): Mongol religious tolerance in law; Mamluk Cairo absorbing the wrecked east's refugees; Sufi orders and charitable endowment (waqf) as the safety net.","wonders":"Rumi writing in Konya as refugees stream past; the Maragha observatory — the destroyer funding astronomy that later reaches Copernicus; Chartres rising in France."},"p9":{"title":"~1500 CE — The 1453–1517 Pivot","languages":"Ottoman Turkish joins Arabic and Persian as the three tongues of Islamic high culture; print standardizes European vernaculars; Spanish and Portuguese go oceanic; Swahili and Malay carry Islam on the trade winds.","money":"Venetian ducat and Ottoman akçe — then American silver: the Spanish peso becomes the first global currency, minted in Mexico, spent in Manila, hoarded in Ming China.","society":"The Ottoman millet system — each religious community self-governing — against Spain's Inquisition and expulsions: the era's starkest moral contrast (Bayezid II sends ships for the expelled Sephardim). Honest note: the devshirme child-levy built careers to Grand Vizier yet was a coerced tribute of children — presented in full complexity.","politics":"Gunpowder centralizes power everywhere — Ottomans, Safavids, Mughals, Ming, Europe's new monarchies; the caliphate consolidates in Istanbul (1517).","economy":"Portugal gate-crashes the Indian Ocean's centuries-old free-trade world with cannon (1498); the Columbian Exchange begins — and American epidemics kill up to ~90% of indigenous peoples within a century: the era's demographic catastrophe.","moral":"Gravest: the American collapse and the opening Atlantic slave trade; the Inquisition. Most equitable (relative): Ottoman confessional pluralism; Timbuktu's scholarship under Songhai; Ming's exam state.","wonders":"Leonardo and Michelangelo work the same decades as Sinan's apprenticeship; Arabic-script printing stays restricted until the 1720s — a consequential divergence, flagged honestly."},"p10":{"title":"~1600 CE — The Three Empires' Noon","languages":"Persian is the court language from Istanbul's chancery style to Delhi's administration; Urdu is being born in the Mughal camp-bazaars (the word means “camp”); English is Shakespeare's, still an island tongue.","money":"The Mughal rupiya (Sher Shah, 1540s) — ancestor of every rupee; Spanish silver flows east, perhaps a third ending in Ming China; the Ottoman akçe inflates under the silver flood — globalization bites a great power for the first time.","society":"Akbar's sulh-i kul — “peace with all” — jizya abolished (later reinstated by Aurangzeb: show the debate); Hindu generals at the Mughal apex; Ottoman coffeehouses invent café public life — coffee itself a Yemeni Sufi gift (pin Mocha).","politics":"Three Muslim empires hold perhaps a third of humanity; Europe fights the wars of religion — the Thirty Years' War kills a third of Germany: religious warfare was no eastern specialty.","economy":"Mughal India ~a quarter of world GDP — the world's textile factory; the joint-stock company is born (EIC 1600, VOC 1602): the corporate form that will conquer more territory than any army.","moral":"Gravest: the Atlantic slave trade industrializing — millions shipped: the timeline's greatest sustained crime beside the American collapse; serfdom re-hardening in eastern Europe. Most equitable (relative): Akbar's pluralist experiment; Ottoman kanun limiting arbitrary punishment; continued refuge for the expelled.","wonders":"The Taj Mahal; the Selimiye; Galileo's telescope (1609) — and Istanbul's Taqi al-Din observatory, built 1577, demolished 1580: an honest paired card on science's diverging paths."},"p11":{"title":"~1800 CE","languages":"English and French become imperial-administrative languages across Asia and Africa; the Bulaq press (Cairo, 1822) industrializes Arabic printing at last; Urdu matures (Mir; Ghalib a generation ahead).","money":"Sterling and the gold standard rise; the Maria Theresa thaler — the coin behind the word “dollar” — is the trusted silver of Arabia and East Africa into the 20th century.","society":"Abolition wins its first victories (trade 1807, slavery 1833) even as colonial exploitation expands — the age's central contradiction, written by slaveholding authors of “all men are created equal”; the Ottoman Tanzimat decrees legal equality of all subjects regardless of religion — on paper the most sweeping such edict of any large state to date.","politics":"The nation-state and the citizen replace dynasty and subject — the tool of colonial domination and, later, of Muslim independence.","economy":"The Industrial Revolution opens the Great Divergence — Britain out-produces the giants (India, China) it is simultaneously de-industrializing; steam and telegraph shrink the map.","moral":"Gravest: the mature Atlantic slave system; Company-era famine in Bengal (1770); opium forced on China. Most equitable (relative): the abolitionists; Tanzimat equality; revolutionary rights-language that the colonized will turn against the colonizers.","wonders":"Vaccination (1796); railways (1825–); photography (1839) — from here the site can show photographs of the places on the map."},"p12":{"title":"~1900 CE","languages":"English becomes the first truly global language by empire, steam and telegraph; French the diplomatic tongue; the Arabic nahda modernizes the press and the novel from Cairo and Beirut.","money":"The classical gold standard at its height — sterling the world's reserve; Ottoman lira, rupee and Egyptian pound pegged into the imperial system.","society":"Racial hierarchy codified in colonial law; indenture replacing slavery in all but name; women's suffrage begins (New Zealand 1893); mass newspapers create public opinion — including the pan-Islamic readership Abdulhamid II cultivates from Istanbul to Singapore.","politics":"Nearly the entire Muslim world under European rule or tutelage — the map's most lopsided frame; Japan's 1905 defeat of Russia electrifies Asia: proof the empires could lose.","economy":"Suez makes Egypt the world's hinge and its debt Britain's excuse; oil struck in Persia (1908) quietly loads the next century.","moral":"Gravest: the Congo Free State's millions dead for rubber; the Indian famines of 1876–1902 under laissez-faire dogma; the coming Armenian catastrophe (1915) inside the collapsing Ottoman state — stated plainly, per this site's rule of flinching at nothing. Most equitable (relative): the first humanitarian law (Geneva 1864, The Hague 1899); constitutional revolutions inside Muslim empires — Ottoman 1908, Persian 1906.","wonders":"Electricity, cars, cinema, radio, flight (1903) — one lifetime's leap; the Hijaz Railway carrying pilgrims by steam."},"p13":{"title":"1924–1945 — Caliphate's End → the New World","languages":"Turkey moves Turkish to Latin script (1928) — a civilizational signal; English consolidates globally; Urdu/Hindi politics foreshadow partition; Modern Standard Arabic unifies a press across new borders.","money":"The gold standard dies in the Depression; at Bretton Woods (1944) the US dollar becomes the anchor of world money — the arrangement the final frame inherits.","society":"Mass politics everywhere — nationalist parties, the Brotherhood (1928), the Pakistan movement (1940); radio propaganda and total war; women enter suffrage and wartime workforces across dozens of states.","politics":"The caliphate abolished (1924) after 1,292 years; mandates and monarchies redraw the Middle East; totalitarianism rises; the war ends with two superpowers, the UN — and empires too broke to hold.","economy":"The Depression discredits laissez-faire; Middle East oil (Bahrain 1932, Dammam 1938, Kuwait 1938) shifts the economic map back toward the region where this timeline began.","moral":"Gravest: the Holocaust — six million Jews murdered: the moral nadir of the entire timeline, stated without qualification; WWII's 70–85 million dead; the Bengal famine of 1943. Most equitable (emerging): the UN Charter and the Universal Declaration ahead (1948) — drafted with Lebanese, Egyptian and soon-Pakistani voices among others; independence movements winning on rights language — Indonesia declares independence in the closing frame.","wonders":"Penicillin, radar, jets, computing — and the atom split over Hiroshima: the final panel ends on this dual note, then fades to the modern map."}},"sources":[["Sarwat Saulat — Millat-e-Islamia ki Mukhtasar Tareekh (Urdu, 5 vols)","https://archive.org/details/millat-e-islamiyah-ki-mukhtasar-tareekh-part-1"],["Ibn Kathir — Al-Bidayah wan-Nihayah (English, Darussalam)","https://archive.org/details/albidayaannihayaallinonepdf"],["Ibn Kathir — Stories of the Prophets","https://archive.org/details/stories-of-the-prophets-by-ibn-kathir-english-pdf"],["Al-Mubarakpuri — Ar-Raheeq Al-Makhtum (The Sealed Nectar)","https://archive.org/details/the-sealed-nectar-ar-raheeq-al-makhtum-english"],["Al-Tabari — History (SUNY English, 40 vols)","https://archive.org/details/tarikh-al-tabari"],["Quran","https://quran.com"],["Hadith","https://sunnah.com"],["McEvedy & Jones — Atlas of World Population History","https://archive.org/details/atlasofworldpopu0000mcev"],["HYDE / Our World in Data — population","https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/world-population-comparison-historical-sources"],["Historical Basemaps — border polygons (CC/GitHub)","https://github.com/aourednik/historical-basemaps"],["World History Encyclopedia","https://www.worldhistory.org"]]};